Expectation and context: the city returns to the center of logistics

For years, the large logistics platforms located in peripheral corridors dominated the European market. Macro-warehouses of tens of thousands of square meters, located far from urban centers and designed to optimize land and storage costs, seemed to represent the definitive future of the sector. However, the growth of e-commerce, rapid deliveries and the pressure to reduce times and emissions are changing that logic.

Now, the focus is beginning to shift toward a different model: urban Multi-let units. Smaller, more flexible logistics spaces close to the end consumer that allow operators, retailers and distribution companies to respond more quickly to an increasingly immediate demand.

The change is not minor. Logistics is no longer measured solely by storage capacity, but by proximity, operational efficiency and adaptability. And in dense cities such as Madrid, Barcelona, Paris or Milan, where available industrial land is scarce, these urban platforms are beginning to become one of the most coveted assets in the European real estate market.

The transition generates a clear sense in the sector: whoever controls the last mile will control a good part of the logistics value chain in the next decade.

While some large rural warehouses continue to face risks of oversupply and greater operational distances, urban Multi-let assets are attracting growing interest for their ability to diversify tenants, reduce vacancy and absorb the demand of medium and small operators who need an immediate presence within or near cities.

The market is beginning to interpret this transformation as something deeper than a temporary trend. For many institutional investors, it is a structural repositioning of the European logistics sector.

Expected impact: flexibility, resilience and pressure on urban land

The main advantage of Multi-let units lies in their operational flexibility. Unlike large single-tenant platforms, these assets allow surfaces to be divided among multiple operators, generating more diversified income and reducing dependence on a single tenant.

In an economic environment where companies seek to adapt quickly to changes in consumption and distribution, this fragmentation capacity becomes an evident competitive advantage.

In addition, the growing demand for same-day deliveries or in increasingly narrow time slots is forcing logistics companies to get physically closer to the consumer. This increases the strategic value of industrial spaces close to large metropolitan areas, where land availability is limited and urban-planning barriers are high.

The consequence is direct: upward pressure on urban logistics rents and greater competition for well-located assets.

At the same time, large-scale rural assets continue to be relevant for mass storage and regional distribution, but some analysts are beginning to question whether part of the expansion developed during recent years could generate supply imbalances in certain peripheral European areas.

This duality is creating a new segmentation within the logistics market. It is no longer enough to "invest in logistics"; the exact location, the proximity to the consumer and the asset's adaptability are beginning to make significant differences in the perception of value and investor demand.

For many investors, the challenge is no longer simply to identify growth, but to understand which part of the logistics chain will capture the most value in an environment where speed has become a critical factor.

What it means for the investor: access, analysis and consolidated vision

In an increasingly specialized market, accessing logistics opportunities with clear and comparable information becomes essential. The fragmentation of the sector makes it difficult to analyze real trends, compare platforms or identify which projects could benefit most from the boom in urban logistics.

Understanding factors such as occupancy, tenant typology, location or exposure to the last mile can make relevant differences in the evaluation of opportunities within European real estate.

